# Digital Audio Guide — Levels and Measurements

**dBFS · dB(Z) · dB(A) · SPL · Bits**

## 1. Audio Samples

An audio file is a sequence of numbers between **-1** and **+1**, called **samples**. Each number represents the position of the speaker membrane at a precise instant.

*   +1.0 = membrane pushed to the maximum forward
*   -1.0 = membrane pulled to the maximum backward
*   0 = silence

At 44,100 Hz, the computer takes **44,100 measurements per second**.


## 2. dBFS (Digital Level)

dBFS measures the amplitude of the digital signal **relative to the maximum possible value (1.0)**.

**From the RMS of the signal:**

$$\text{RMS} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i^2}$$

$$\text{dBFS} = 20 \times \log_{10}(\text{RMS})$$

**From Windows volume percentage:**

$$\text{dBFS} = 20 \times \log_{10}\left(\frac{p}{100}\right)$$

where $p$ = Windows volume in % (the % character did not work inside the fraction)

> Note: this formula assumes the audio file is at 0 dBFS. If your file is at -10 dBFS: dBFS = dBFS_source + 20 × log10(% / 100) = -10 + 20 × log10(% / 100)

**Properties:**

*   Always negative or zero (you cannot exceed 1.0)
*   0 dBFS = absolute maximum
*   -30 dBFS = signal at 3.16% of the maximum

**Examples:**

|Windows %|dBFS     |
|---------|---------|
|100%     |0 dBFS   |
|50%      |-6 dBFS  |
|10%      |-20 dBFS |


## 3. From dBFS to dB SPL (Z) — the MAX_SPL

**dB SPL** (Sound Pressure Level) is the actual acoustic pressure in the air. To go from digital to acoustic, you need the hardware specs.

$$\text{MAX\\_SPL} = S_{\text{dBmW}} + 10 \times \log_{10}\left(\frac{V_{\text{out}}^2}{R} \times 1000\right)$$

$$\text{dB(Z) SPL} = \text{MAX\\_SPL} + \text{dBFS}$$

> where dBFS = dBFS_source + Pre-Amp + 20 × log10(% / 100)

**Parameters:**

*   $S_{\text{dB/mW}}$ : headphone sensitivity in dB/mW
*   $V_{\text{out}}$ : DAC output voltage in Vrms
*   $R$ : headphone impedance in Ω
*   $\times 1000$ : watts → milliwatts conversion

**Numerical example:**

- Headphones Artti T10 : 96 dB/mW, 16.5 Ω - DAC : 1.2 Vrms - Peace UI Equalizer APO : -30 Pre-Amp - dBFS_source : -10 dBFS - Windows volume : 50%.

$$\text{MAX\\_SPL} = 96 + 10 \times \log_{10}\left(\frac{1.2^2}{16.5} \times 1000\right) = 115.4 \text{ dB SPL}$$

$$\text{vol\\_dB} = 20 \times \log_{10}\left(\frac{50}{100}\right) = 20 \times \log_{10}(0.5) = -6 \text{ dB}$$

$$\text{dBFS} = \text{dBFS\\_source} + \text{Pre-Amp} + \text{vol\\_dB} = -10 + (-30) + (-6) = -46 \text{ dBFS}$$

$$\text{dB(Z) SPL} = 115.4 + (-46) = 69.4 \text{ dB(Z) SPL}$$

> Note: the dB(Z) SPL calculated assumes a neutral headphone. In reality, two other factors modify the level at each frequency: the hardware frequency response (Hardware Response) and the software EQ (Peace/APO), if you use one. Both add up: dB(Z) SPL final = MAX_SPL + dBFS + HW(f) + EQ(f)


## 4. The A-Filter — Ear Weighting

The human ear does not hear all frequencies equally. The A-filter mimics this sensitivity. For each frequency $f$ (in Hz):

$$R_A(f) = \frac{12194^2 \cdot f^4}{\left(f^2 + 20.6^2\right) \cdot \sqrt{\left(f^2 + 107.7^2\right)\left(f^2 + 737.9^2\right)} \cdot \left(f^2 + 12194^2\right)}$$

$$G_A(f) = 20 \times \log_{10}(R_A(f)) + 2.00$$

**Typical values:**

|Frequency |Sound type  |$G_A(f)$  |Effect              |
|----------|------------|----------|--------------------|
|50 Hz     |Deep bass   |-30.2 dB  |Strongly attenuated |
|1,000 Hz  |Human voice |≈ 0 dB    |Reference, unchanged|
|4,000 Hz  |Whistle     |+1 dB     |Slightly amplified  |
|10,000 Hz |Cymbals     |-2.5 dB   |Slightly attenuated |


## 5. dB(A) — Full Formula

$$\text{dB(A)} = \text{MAX\\_SPL} + \text{dBFS\\_source} + \text{Pre-Amp} + 20\log_{10}\left(\frac{p}{100}\right) + \text{HW}(f) + \text{EQ}(f) + G_A(f)$$

*   $\text{dBFS\\_source}$ : audio file level
*   $\text{Pre-Amp}$ : Peace/APO pre-amplification in dB (negative = attenuation, positive = gain)
*   $p$ : Windows volume in %
*   $\text{HW}(f)$ : hardware frequency response (headphones) at frequency f
*   $\text{EQ}(f)$ : gain applied by the software equalizer at frequency f
*   $G_A(f)$ : A-filter gain at frequency f (section 4)

Or more simply:

$$\text{dB(A)} = \text{dB(Z) SPL} + G_A(f)$$

**In practice**, a music signal contains hundreds of simultaneous frequencies. $G_A(f)$ is calculated for each frequency (via FFT), then all contributions are summed.

**Example:**

- Same headphones, Artti T10 - 50% Windows - dBFS_source : 0 dBFS - Pre-Amp : 0 dB - HW(1000 Hz) : 0 dB - EQ(1000 Hz) : 0 dB - frequency 1,000 Hz :

$$\text{vol\\_dB} = 20 \times \log_{10}\left(\frac{50}{100}\right) = -6 \text{ dB}$$

$$\text{dB(A)} = 115.4 + 0 + 0 + (-6) + 0 + 0 + 0.1 = 109.5 \text{ dB(A)}$$

**Dangerous** — prolonged exposure not recommended beyond a few minutes.


## 6. Formula Summary

|Calculation          |Formula                                                                |
|---------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|
|Volume factor        |10^(dBFS/20)                                                           |
|dBFS from Windows %  |20 × log10(% / 100)                                                    |
|RMS of signal        |sqrt( (1/n) × sum(xi²) )                                               |
|dBFS from RMS        |20 × log10(RMS)                                                        |
|MAX_SPL              |S + 10 × log10(V² / R × 1000)                                          |
|dBFS                 |dBFS_source + Pre-Amp + 20 × log10(% / 100)                            |
|dB(Z) SPL            |MAX_SPL + dBFS + HW(f) + EQ(f)                                         |
|R_A(f)               |12194² × f⁴ / ((f²+20.6²) × sqrt((f²+107.7²)(f²+737.9²)) × (f²+12194²))|
|A-filter gain        |20 × log10(RA(f)) + 2                                                  |
|dB(A) SPL            |dB(Z) SPL + GA(f)                                                      |

**Danger thresholds (WHO / NIOSH):** 80 dB(A) over 40h/week / 85 dB(A) over 8h/day


## 7. Resolution — Bits

A sample is a number. But on a computer, not all numbers are equal. A number can be stored with more or less precision depending on how many **bits** are allocated to it.

*   2 bits = 4 possible values
*   8 bits = 256 possible values
*   16 bits = 65,536 possible values
*   24 bits = 16,777,216 possible values

Applied to sound: your membrane must move between -1 and +1. With 16 bits, you divide this range into 65,536 possible positions. With 24 bits, into 16 million positions.

The more bits you have, the more precisely the membrane position can be described. The fewer bits, the more the sound sounds "staircase-like" — this is called **quantization distortion**.

```
Amplitude
+1.0 |    ****        ****
     |   *    *      *    *
+0.5 |  *------*    *  ----*-
     | *       |*  *  |     *|
 0.0 |*        | **   |      *
     |         |      |      |*        *
-0.5 |          ------        -*------*-
     |                          *    *
-1.0 |                           ****
     +---------------------------------> Time
      ~~~~ ideal signal
      ---- 1 bit signal (staircase)
```

1 bit doubles the number of available levels. Doubling the amplitude corresponds to +6 dB:

$$20 \times \log_{10}(2) = 6.02 \text{ dB}$$

So each bit adds 6 dB of dynamic range. For 16 bits:

$$20 \times \log_{10}(2^{16}) = 20 \times 16 \times \log_{10}(2) = 96 \text{ dB}$$

*   2 bits  = 12 dB of dynamic range
*   16 bits = 96 dB of dynamic range
*   24 bits = 144 dB of dynamic range

### Resolution is not the same everywhere

In 16 bits, the 65,536 levels are not evenly distributed across the dBFS range. Each 6 dBFS slice contains **half the levels** of the slice above it.

```
dBFS  | Available levels (16 bits)    | Bits used
------+-------------------------------+----------
  0   |                               |
      | 32,768 levels (2¹⁵)           | bit 16
 -6   |                               |
      | 16,384 levels (2¹⁴)           | bit 15
-12   |                               |
      |  8,192 levels (2¹³)           | bit 14
-18   |                               |
      |  4,096 levels (2¹²)           | bit 13
-24   |                               |
      |  2,048 levels (2¹¹)           | bit 12
-30   | <-- your sound is here        |
      |  1,024 levels (2¹⁰)           | bit 11
-36   |                               |
```

A sound at **-30 dBFS** only uses 11 bits out of 16. The slice between -30 and -24 dBFS contains only 2,048 levels to describe all the nuances of the sound. The slice between -6 and 0 dBFS contains 32,768 — that is **16 times more precision**.

This is why you always record as close to 0 dBFS as possible without clipping: to use the maximum number of available levels and get the most precise sound possible.
